[[Ship-of-the-Line Captain|Captain]] '''Wolfgang August Eugen L<U+00FC>th''' (15 October 1913 &ndash; 14 May 1945) was the second most successful [[Germany|German]] [[U-Boat|U-boat]] [[Aces of the Deep|ace]] of [[World War II]]. His career record of 46 merchant ships plus the French submarine ''Doris'' sunk during 15 war patrols, with a total displacement of {{GRT|230,781|metric|first=yes}}, was second only to that of ''[[Korvettenkapit<U+00E4>n]]'' [[Otto Kretschmer]], whose 47 sinkings totaled {{GRT|272,958|metric}}.{{ref label|Note1|a|a}}<ref name="Williamson p19">Williamson 2006, p. 19.</ref>

L<U+00FC>th joined the [[Reichsmarine]] in 1933. After a period of training on surface vessels he transferred to the U-boat service in 1936. In December 1939 he received command of [[German submarine U-9 (1935)|''U-9'']], which he took on six war-patrols. In June 1940 he took command of [[German submarine U-138 (1940)|''U-138'']] for two patrols. In October 1940 he transferred again, this time to the ocean-going [[German submarine U-43 (1939)|''U-43'']] submarine for five war-patrols. After two war-patrols, the second being his longest of the war, on [[German submarine U-181|''U-181'']] he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross#Knight's Cross with Oak Leaves, Swords, and Diamonds (mit Eichenlaub, Schwertern und Brillianten)|Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves, Swords, and Diamonds]] (''Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub, Schwertern und Brillianten''). He was the first of two U-boat commanders to be honored in such a way during World War II, the other recipient being [[Albrecht Brandi]].

L<U+00FC>th's last service position was commander of the [[Naval Academy M<U+00FC>rwik]] at [[Flensburg]]-M<U+00FC>rwik. He was accidentally shot and killed by a German sentry on the night of 13 to 14 May 1945. L<U+00FC>th was given the last [[state funeral]] of the [[Third Reich]], the only U-boat commander to be so honored.<ref name="Kurowski p153">Kurowski 1995, p. 153.</ref>

==Biography==
L<U+00FC>th was a [[Baltic German]] born in [[Riga]] in the [[Russian Empire]]. Here he went to the [[Gymnasium (school)|Naturwissenschaftliches Gymnasium]] and, after he had received his [[Abitur]], he studied Law for three semesters at the Herder-Institut. With his parents approval he joined the [[Reichsmarine]]{{ref label|Note2|b|b}} on 1 April 1933. After he received his military basic training he was transferred to the [[school ship]] [[Gorch Fock (1933)|''Gorch Fock'']] attaining the rank of ''[[Midshipman|Seekadett]]'' on 23 September, 1933. He served with surface fleet at first, going on a 9-month training tour around the world in the [[German cruiser Karlsruhe|light cruiser ''Karlsruhe'']] in 1934, and served for a year aboard the [[German cruiser K<U+00F6>nigsberg|light cruiser ''K<U+00F6>nigsberg'']].<ref>Alman 1988, p. 8.</ref>

In February 1937 he transferred to the U-boat arm. In July he was appointed 2nd Watch Officer of [[German submarine U-27 (1936)|''U-27'']], with which he sailed on a patrol in [[Spain|Spanish]] waters during the [[Spanish Civil War]]. In October he was appointed the 1st Watch Officer of [[German submarine U-38 (1938)|''U-38'']] under the command of ''[[Kapit<U+00E4>nleutnant]]'' [[Heinrich Liebe]], who during the course of World War II would earn the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross#Knight's Cross with Oak Leaves (mit Eichenlaub)|Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves]] (''Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub''). L<U+00FC>th was on patrol with ''U-38'' when the war started on 1 September 1939.<ref name="Berger p190">Berger 1999, p. 190.</ref>

===On board ''U-9''===
On 30 December 1939 L<U+00FC>th took command of [[German submarine U-9 (1935)|''U-9'']], a [[Type II U-boat#Type IIB|Type IIB U-boat]]. With this boat he went on six war-patrols, achieving successes steadily, including sinking the [[France|French]] submarine ''Doris'' on 9 May 1940 and 7 merchant ships of {{GRT|16,669|metric|first=yes}}. Two of L<U+00FC>th's officers on ''U-9'' would be awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] (''Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes''). His ''Leitender Ingenieur'' (chief engineer) ''[[Oberleutnant zur See]]'' [[Karl-Heinz Wiebe]] received the Knight's Cross in 1944 as chief engineer of [[German submarine U-178|''U-178'']]. ''Oberleutnant zur See'' [[Heinrich Schonder]], 1st Watch Officer on ''U-9'' between January and April 1940, earned the award in 1942 as commander of [[German submarine U-77 (1940)|''U-77'']].<ref name="Berger p190"/>

===On board ''U-138''===
On 27 June 1940 L<U+00FC>th took command of [[German submarine U-138 (1940)|''U-138'']], a [[Type II U-boat#Type IID|Type IID]], with which he sunk 4 ships on his first patrol, totalling {{GRT|34,644|metric}}. In October, after having returned from his second patrol, on which he torpedoed (but missed) the Norwegian merchant steamer ''Dagrun'' ({{GRT|4,562|metric}}), sank the British merchant steamer ''Bonheur'' ({{GRT|5,327|metric}}) and damaged the British motor tanker ''British Glory'' ({{GRT|6,993|metric}}). L<U+00FC>th was mentioned for the first time in the daily ''[[Wehrmachtbericht]]'' on 23 September 1940 and received the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross (''Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes'') for his achievements on 24 October 1940.<ref name="Berger p190"/>

===On board ''U-43''===
On 21 October 1940 L<U+00FC>th took command of [[German submarine U-43 (1939)|''U-43'']], a long range [[Type IX U-boat]]. With this boat he made five patrols totaling 204 days at sea, sinking 12 ships adding up to {{GRT|64,852|metric}}. On 1 January 1941 he was promoted to ''[[Kapit<U+00E4>nleutnant]]''. L<U+00FC>th, because of his experience &mdash; like many other top commanders &mdash; was tasked to train future U-boat commanders. These U-boat commander trainees often came along on single war-patrols, which would be their last exercise before they received their own U-boat  command. ''Kapit<U+00E4>nleutnant'' [[Erich W<U+00FC>rdemann]] was one of L<U+00FC>th's trainees and sailed onboard of ''U-43'' from April to July 1941. W<U+00FC>rdemann would be awarded the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross as commander of [[German submarine U-506|U-506]] in 1943 before he was [[killed in action]] on 14 July 1943.<ref>Range 1974, p. 182.</ref>

===On board ''U-181''===
On 9 May 1942 L<U+00FC>th was given command of a long-range [[Type IX U-boat#Type IXD|Type IXD-2]] U-boat, [[German submarine U-181|''U-181'']]. He left on his first patrol in September 1942, departing from [[Kiel]]. The target of this patrol was the [[Indian Ocean]] and [[South Africa]]n waters. In October he reached the sea lanes outside [[Cape Town]] and spent a month patrolling, sinking 12 ships for  {{GRT|58,381|metric}} before returning to [[Bordeaux]], France, in January 1943. On 13 November 1942 he received the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross#Knight's Cross with Oak Leaves (mit Eichenlaub)|Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves]] (''Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub'').<ref>Williamson 2006, p. 18.</ref>

In March 1943 L<U+00FC>th set out for a second patrol off South Africa into the [[Indian Ocean]] and in particular the waters around [[Mauritius]]. This patrol lasted 205 days (23 March 1943 &ndash; 14 October 1943) making it the second longest of the war (The longest combat patrol of World War II was 225 days in length, and this was achieved by [[Eitel-Friedrich Kentrat]] as commander of the [[German submarine U-196|''U-196'']].) L<U+00FC>th sank 10 ships totaling {{GRT|45,331|metric}} on this patrol, which turned out to be his last. While on patrol he was promoted to ''[[Korvettenkapit<U+00E4>n]]'' on 1 April 1943, and on 15 April 1943 received news that he had been awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross#Knight's Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords (mit Eichenlaub und Schwertern)|Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords]] (''Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub und Schwertern'').<ref name="Williamson p19"/>

''U-181'' rendezvoused with the supply ship ''Charlotte Schliemann'' east of Mauritius to refuel on 21 June 1943. Also present at the supply point were [[German submarine U-177|''U-177'']] under the command of [[Robert Gysae]], [[German submarine U-178|''U-178'']] under the command of [[Wilhelm Dommes]], [[German submarine U-196|''U-196'']] under the command of Eitel-Friedrich Kentrat, [[German submarine U-197|''U-197'']] under the command of Robert Bartels and [[German submarine U-198|''U-198'']] under the command of [[Werner Hartmann]]. Here the commanders exchanged experiences and discussed the problem of torpedo failures. On 9 August of the same year and still on patrol, L<U+00FC>th was awarded the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves, Swords and Diamonds (''Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub, Schwertern und Brillianten'').<ref name="Williamson p19"/><ref>Alman 1988, pp. 159&ndash;161.</ref>

L<U+00FC>th nominated two crew members of ''U-181'' for the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross after this patrol. The chief engineer [[Kapit<U+00E4>nleutnant]] [[Carl-August Landfermann]] and 2nd Watch Officer [[Johannes Limbach]] both received the Knight's Cross for their achievements.<ref>Kurowski 1995, pp. 131, 149.</ref>

After five years of operational U-boat service, including 15 war-patrols and over 600 days at sea, L<U+00FC>th took command of [[22. Unterseebootsflottille]] in January 1944. This was a training unit for U-boat commanders. In July 1944 he took command of the 1st Department of the ''[[Naval Academy M<U+00FC>rwik|Marineschule M<U+00FC>rwik]]'' (Naval Academy M<U+00FC>rwik) in [[Flensburg]]-M<U+00FC>rwik. He was promoted to ''[[Fregattenkapit<U+00E4>n]]'' on 1 August 1944 and became the commander of the entire ''Marineschule'' in September, and advanced in rank to ''[[Kapit<U+00E4>n zur See]]''.<ref name="Williamson p19"/>

===Death===
[[File:L<U+00FC>th funeral.JPG|thumb|right|Wolfgang L<U+00FC>th's state funeral, ''Gro<U+00DF>admiral'' Karl D<U+00F6>nitz at the far right delivering the eulogy]]
The British Forces had occupied [[Flensburg]] on 5 May 1945, though initially nothing changed in the daily routine at the Naval Academy M<U+00FC>rwik. On the night of 13 to 14 May 1945 L<U+00FC>th was shot in the head by 18 year-old ''[[Matrose]]'' Mathias Gottlob, a German sentry at the Flensburg-M<U+00FC>rwik Naval Academy, when he failed to respond to the sentry's challenge. The password of the day was "Tannenberg". Whether he deliberately failed to respond, perhaps in order to commit suicide, or if the guard simply did not hear his response, is unknown. The officer in charge immediately informed ''[[Gro<U+00DF>admiral]]'' [[Karl D<U+00F6>nitz]]. D<U+00F6>nitz adjudant ''[[Fregattenkapit<U+00E4>n]]'' Walter L<U+00FC>dde-Neurath, who accepted the call, initially thought that this was a bad joke. L<U+00FC>dde-Neurath then informed L<U+00FC>th's brother, Joachim L<U+00FC>th, as the two brothers were staying together. It was he who informed L<U+00FC>th's wife and their four children that L<U+00FC>th had died.<ref>Alman 1988, pp. 13, 14.</ref>

D<U+00F6>nitz contacted the British city commander of Flensburg, Colonel Roberts, asking him for a permission to conduct a formal [[state funeral]], which Roberts approved. The last state funeral of the Third Reich was held for L<U+00FC>th on 16 May 1945 with [[Adolf Hitler]]'s successor as Head of State, ''[[Reichspr<U+00E4>sident]]'' and ''Gro<U+00DF>admiral'' Karl D<U+00F6>nitz, delivering the eulogy.<ref>Berger 1999, p. 192.</ref> Six U-boat commanders, all of them recipients of the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross, formed the [[honour guard]].<ref>Alman 1988, p. 15.</ref>

D<U+00F6>nitz ordered a board of inquiry and [[court martial]] to clarify the circumstances of the deadly shooting. Four officers under the command of a Navy Judge conducted the court martial. Mathias Gottlob stated that, according to his orders, had asked for the password three times without response from the person, whom he could not visually identify in the darkness. Without aiming he had fired his rifle from the hip. The chain of events was confirmed by the ''Maschinenmaat'' Karl Franz, who was leading the watch at the time. The court ruled that Gottlob was not guilty and he was cleared of any fault in the killing of ''Kapit<U+00E4>n zur See'' Wolfgang L<U+00FC>th.<ref>Alman 1988, p. 16.</ref>

==Summary of career==
During his career L<U+00FC>th sunk 46 commercial ships for {{GRT|225,204|metric}}, one warship of {{GRT|552|metric}}, and damaged two ships for  {{GRT|17,343|metric}}.<ref>Alman 1988, pp. 282, 283.</ref> His last patrol saw ''U-181'' at sea for 206 days, patrolling the waters beween [[Capetown]] and [[Madagascar]], making it the second-longest patrol of the war.<ref name="Kurowski p153"/>

